	painsBodyHtml={`<p>Behind every statistic is a real responder — maybe you. The call that replays at 3 a.m. The face you couldn't save. The way your body stays braced for the next tone even on your day off. The unspoken rule that you're supposed to be the strong one, so you swallow it and show up again tomorrow.</p><p>None of this means something is wrong with you. It means you're human, carrying things no human was built to carry alone — and the culture that calls you a hero often forgets you bleed too. There is a Father who sees the real you underneath the uniform, who knows every call you carry, and who has something to say about who you actually are.</p>`}
	painsSources={[
		{ label: `SAMHSA — First Responders and Disaster Responders Resource Portal`, url: `https://www.samhsa.gov/resource/dbhis/first-responders-disaster-responders-resource-portal` },
		{ label: `Ruderman Family Foundation — White Paper on Mental Health and Suicide of First Responders`, url: `https://rudermanfoundation.org/white_papers/police-officers-and-firefighters-are-more-likely-to-die-by-suicide-than-in-line-of-duty/` },
		{ label: `CDC / NIOSH — Emergency Response Resources`, url: `https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/emres/` },
